"mesh:D011284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "pregnenolone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997045397758484, "span": {"begin": 665, "end": 677}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993454813957214, "span": {"begin": 729, "end": 736}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999631404876709, "span": {"begin": 756, "end": 764}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9933323860168457, "span": {"begin": 804, "end": 816}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "steroidal", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9960596561431885, "span": {"begin": 820, "end": 829}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989306330680847, "span": {"begin": 953, "end": 962}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9944720268249512, "span": {"begin": 1026, "end": 1038}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954508543014526, "span": {"begin": 1062, "end": 1074}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgens", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9976502060890198, "span": {"begin": 1107, "end": 1116}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9937703013420105, "span": {"begin": 1134, "end": 1146}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "trout fish", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.6983686685562134, "span": {"begin": 1290, "end": 1300}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:8038"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Salvelinus fontinalis", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9274168014526367, "span": {"begin": 1302, "end": 1323}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6770", "2984"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "StAR protein", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9967355728149414, "span": {"begin": 1344, "end": 1356}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "steroidal", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9816648364067078, "span": {"begin": 1499, "end": 1508}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9989262223243713, "span": {"begin": 1558, "end": 1566}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "estrogen receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918662309646606, "span": {"begin": 1558, "end": 1576}}], "text": "Steroidogenic acute regulatory (StAR) protein (37-kDa) is synthesized with a mitochondrial leader sequence in response to the cell stimulation to produce steroid and plays a crucial role in steroidogenesis (Hanukoglu, 1992).&nbsp; Research had shown in human ovary StAR protein was produced in response to the Luteinizing Hormone (LH) surge (Kiriakidou et al., 1996). In particular, StAR protein involved in the transportation of the cholesterol (substrate for steroid hormone) from outer to inner mitochondrial membrane. This step is crucial and rate limiting in steroid biosynthesis. In the inner membrane of the mitochondria with the help of cleaved cholesterol pregnenolone is formed, which is the precursor to the different steroid hormones including estrogen (P. R. Manna et al., 2016). Effects of StAR protein on steroidal biosynthesis had been studied by number of researchers (Pulak R Manna et al., 2002; Pescador et al., 1996; Stocco, 2001).  Estradiol synthesis during menstrual cycle is governed via expression of StAR protein synthesis. Presence of StAR protein allows follicular production of androgens which allows the progesterone dominated microenvironment and help in sexual differentiation, growth, reproduction, development and metabolism. Kusakabe et al., had shown in trout fish (Salvelinus fontinalis) model that peak of StAR protein coincide with the menstrual hormone production peak (Kusakabe et al., 2002). Research had shown some toxic chemicals can caused alteration in steroidal regulation and resulted in the agonist effect on estrogen receptors (Lauretta et al., 2019).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:41:40 +0000 2026"}